s. Since the base URL is empty, I'll leave the official_doc_urls as an empty array, and I should reconsider whether s4 needs a title even though it appears blank in the expected sections.\n\nLooking back at the instructions, I need exactly 5 sections to match the expected count, so I'll keep s4 as a minimal section. Each section needs at least one hint, so I'll add something minimal for s4 as well. Now I'm examining the source content between s3 and s5 to determine what should go in that empty section—it looks like there's a note about SQL file writing rules that might belong there. s5 also contains only reference material pointing to map-save-label and object-select-label, so it's genuinely \"なし\" for substantive content. Both s4 and s5 are pure referral sections with no Layer A/B material, so I'll mark them accordingly and use the RST labels as hints.\n\nNow I'm constructing the complete JSON output with proper escaping for newlines and special characters in the string values. I'm noting that when combining arrays with variable conditions, the collection gets excluded from the WHERE clause if it's null or empty, but included if it has elements—though individual array elements can't be used in conditional logic. There are also important warnings: IN clause dynamic generation should only be used in web applications since batch processing needs fixed SQL for performance reasons, and Map interface implementations aren't supported in condition objects.\n\nFor dynamic ORDER BY clauses, I need to use `ParameterizedSqlPStatement` with the `$sort()` directive, setting up a property in the form class that corresponds to the sort field name to control how results are ordered.\n\nWhen `sortId` is set to `\"3\"`, the framework generates SQL that orders by the specified field—in this case `USER_NAME`. There's an important caveat though: dynamic ORDER BY modifications should only be used in web applications, not batch processing, since the SQL construction overhead degrades perf